TY  - JOUR
T1  - Does National Culture or Ambient Temperature Explain Cross-National Differences in Role Stress? No Sweat!
AU  - Peterson, Mark F.
AU  - Smith, Peter B.
Y1  - 1997/08/01
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256953
DO  - 10.5465/256953
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 930
EP  - 946
VL  - 40
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Van de Vliert and Van Yperen's (1996) proposal that ambient temperature explains the relationship between national cultural values and typical levels of role stress is reevaluated. The provisional conclusion is that the effect of ambient temperature on role stress is largely mediated by its contribution to the historical evolution of cultural values.
AB  - Van de Vliert and Van Yperen's (1996) proposal that ambient temperature explains the relationship between national cultural values and typical levels of role stress is reevaluated. The provisional conclusion is that the effect of ambient temperature on role stress is largely mediated by its contribution to the historical evolution of cultural values.
